{"accepted":[{"assertion":"Formal-Conjectures statement: Erdos318.erdos_318.parts.i https://google-deepmind.github.io/formal-conjectures/theorem/?name=Erdos318.erdos_318.parts.i.","id":"vf_26ee032f9940a8da","trust":"signed","type":"theoretical"},{"assertion":"Erdős Problem #318: declared status 'solved'. Formalized: yes. Let $A\\subseteq \\mathbb{N}$ be an infinite arithmetic progression and $f:A\\to \\{-1,1\\}$ be a non-constant function. Must there exist a finite non-empty $S\\subset A$ such that\\[\\sum_{n\\in S}\\frac{f(n)}{n}=0?\\]What about if $A$ is an arbitrary set of positive density? What if $A$ is the set of squares excluding $1$? Current best: For the squares $1$ must be excluded or the result is trivially false, since\\[\\sum_{k\\geq 2}\\frac{1}{k^2}<1.\\]This is false for some sets $A$ of positive density - indeed, it fails for any set $A$ containing exactly one even number. Prize: no. Tags: number theory, unit fractions.","id":"vf_80c1f18bc08ce39c","trust":"signed","type":"theoretical"}],"accepted_activity":false,"activity":[],"activity_types":[],"attempt_count":0,"banked_attempt_count":0,"commits":[],"dependency_impact":"none","detail_url":"problems/318.json","draft_proposals":[],"edges":[{"evidence":"Problem identity derived from the accepted finding's pinned source anchor.","inferred":true,"relation":"describes","source":"vf_26ee032f9940a8da","source_root":"sha256:540d4967071425f77c693e61f62053208b07d67667490dcb9eeef62ec3f1d316","target":"erdos:318","trust":"signed"},{"evidence":"Materialized typed link between accepted findings.","inferred":true,"relation":"synthesized_from","source":"vf_26ee032f9940a8da","source_root":"sha256:540d4967071425f77c693e61f62053208b07d67667490dcb9eeef62ec3f1d316","target":"vf_80c1f18bc08ce39c","trust":"signed"},{"evidence":"Problem identity derived from the accepted finding's pinned source anchor.","inferred":true,"relation":"describes","source":"vf_80c1f18bc08ce39c","source_root":"sha256:540d4967071425f77c693e61f62053